div.p:
Therfore to bleſſe [
                  〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉
               ] is not heere taken for to conſecrate with a magicall murmuring, by vertue of wordes: yet are the bread and wine chaunged, though not in nature, but in quality. For they are made Symbols of the body & bloud of Chriſt, not by their owne nature, nor yet by force of wordes, but by the inſtitution of Chriſt, which ought to be rehearſed and opened: that faith may haue what to embrace, both in the word, & in the Elements. Muſcu. Loc. com. 397.

A. Two, as;


1. The outward ſigne:

2. The indward holy thing.

This thing doth David point out vnto vs, whē he ſaith, Pſ. 32.1, 2. verſes as, Bleſſed (
                  〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉
               ) is hee whoſe vvickednes is forgiven, and whoſe ſin is covered.

Secōdly, it muſt be reall & true, therfore not imaginatorie or accidentall: namely as the braunches with the vine, as the ſtones of the wall with the whole building, as the members of mans body with the head, and as the coupling of man and wife [
                  〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉
               ] in one fleſh (according to Gods ordinance) be they never ſo far a ſunder in reſpect of place. Epheſ, 5, cap, 29, 30.

The ſubiect or proper ſeate of which forenamed faith muſt be [
                  〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉
               ] the verie nobleſt part, the hart it ſelfe of man. Eph. 3. cap. 17. verſe. And hence we may know the cauſe, why the Lord requireth it, and maketh ſo often mention thereof. As, Prov. 23.26. My Sonne giue me thy heart. Beſides, ſee theſe places, Pſal. 119, 1, 2. Deut. 4, 29. Deut. 6, 5 6. 1, Sam. 16, 7. Rom. 10, cap. 10, verſe.

Firſt, becauſe it reſteth vpon an external ſigne & miracle done, neglecting the waightier matters which are required in the Sacramentes, as to beleeve [
                     〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉
                  ] moſt aſſuredly the promiſes of God, (made vnto vs in his Sonne Chriſt Ieſus,) who is ever faithful and true and readie to performe on his behalfe: and therefore whoſoever doth apprehēd them by a ſtedfaſt faith, he ſhal obteine them ſuer enough without the helpe of miracles: whereof they haue ſuch abūdance, that they do even baske themſelves therein. ſee, 2, Theſsal, 2. cap. 9. ver. Math, 24. chap, 24. verſe. Revel, 13. cap, 13. v. Revel. 16. cap. 14. v.

1 The ſhedding of his blood by which he vvas made that ſame (victima cruenta) bloody ſacrifice for vs, & that but onlie once neither: as for that (victima 

                     〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉
                  ) bloodleſſe ſacrifice, he neuer was ſuch, and the whole courſe of ſcripture, doth gaine-ſay it.
